{
  "answer": "**Iqbal's \"Bilad-e-Islamiya\"** is Chapter 2 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* (1924), a collection of Urdu poetry by Allama Iqbal.[^1] \n\nThis poem is a lyrical survey of historic Islamic cities—Delhi, Baghdad, Cordoba, Constantinople (Istanbul), and Medina (Yathrib)—celebrating them as sacred abodes (*bilad*) of Islam's majesty, civilization, and spiritual legacy.[^2] It evokes their role in Muslim history, from the Prophet's successors to imperial grandeur, while lamenting decline and affirming enduring sanctity.[^3]\n\nRead the full translation here: [/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/02-bilad-e-islamiya/translation/](...)[^2]\n\n[^1]: [*Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, metadata](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, Chapter 2: \"Bilad-e-Islamiya\" ([/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/02-bilad-e-islamiya/translation/](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/02-bilad-e-islamiya/translation/)).\n\n[^3]: e.g., \"[p-3015c7] The Abodes of Islam\" through \"[p-c3029f] As long as you endure on this earth, we too shall endure;\" (*ibid.*).",
